objectives:
Organizing business processes in an efficient and effective manner is the overarching objective of business process management, i.e. an area that is concerned with various management activities that are related to business processes. A variety of representation formats can be used to capture process information in informational artifacts, including process models (e.g., using notations such as Business Process Model and Notation (BPMN)) and natural language descriptions (i.e., textual documents where several actors are mentioned, and their actions and interactions are described). Since the manual elicitation and creation of process models is a time-intensive endeavor, natural language processing techniques can perhaps be applied to automatically derive process models from textual process descriptions.

Goals: 

• Study recent advances in neural approaches for NLP (e.g., for extracting predicates and involved actors via semantic parsing, performing word sense disambiguation to identify domain objects that may be mentioned using different words, solving coreferences, etc.);

• Implementation of methods for deriving process models from textual descriptions, leveraging the aforementioned advances;

References

• Natural Language in Business Process Models: Theoretical Foundations, Techniques, and Applications ( https://sci-hub.se/10.1007/978-3-319-04175-9 );

