objectives:
A gazetteer corresponds to a database storing information on places, each with a stable identifier and some number of descriptive properties (e.g., alternative names and the physical location). Specifically within the context of digital humanities projects, gazetteers support several functions in connection to geographic information retrieval:

- They can provide answers to &quot;where is&quot; questions (e.g., where is Lisbon?);
- They inform users of alternative names for places, or about how names have evolved over time;
- They translate between geographic names and physical locations, i.e., between names and (often vague) geospatial footprints;
- They allow users to locate particular types of geographic features in a designated area;

The development of large coverage gazetteers typically requires the integration of multiple data sources, a task which involves many challenges in terms of data management. This research projects concerns the development of a software framework for managing gazetteer data, supporting the assembly of place names and annotations from multiple data sources, and considering graphical and programmatic interfaces for using and contributing to the gazetteer.

Goals:

- Analyse the data models proposed in previous projects concerned with gazetteer development, specifically the Alexandria Digital Library Gazetteer Content Standard, and the Linked Places format from the World Historical Gazetteer;
- Implement a database and web application for supporting the management of gazetteer data;
- Implement and evaluate data integration procedures for conflating gazetteer data from multiple sources, including procedures for estimating spatio-temporal metadata for the place records;

References:

- Who&#39;s on First Gazetteer ( https://www.whosonfirst.org , https://library.stanford.edu/blogs/digital-library-blog/2018/05/whos-first-stanford );
- World-Historical Gazetteer ( http://whgazetteer.org and http://whgazetteer.org/pubs/WHG-project-plan_Feb2018.pdf );

