objectives:
Community-contributed images, e.g. available at websites such as Flickr, often indicate the location where they were acquired, and, thus, potentially contain a wealth of information about what-is-where on the surface of the Earth. Several recent studies have proposed a novel analysis framework termed proximate sensing, exploring the visual content of geo-referenced ground-level images to extract and map geographically relevant information. While accurate land cover mapping can be achieved with satellite imagery, tasks such as mapping land use (e.g., discriminating between residential and commercial areas) is considerably more difficult and is generally not possible using overhead imagery, as these tasks require close-up views or analyzing building facades. This project will explore recent computer vision methods based on deep neural networks for the classification of geo-referenced ground-level photos, envisioning the creation of maps through proximate sensing.

Goals:

- Study deep learning methods for image classification;
- Development and evaluation of an approach for mapping urban areas, leveraging deep learning methods for the analysis of ground-level Imagery;

References:

- Georeferenced Social Multimedia as Volunteered Geographic Information ( https://sci-hub.tw/10.1007/978-94-024-1531-5_12 );

